WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.030
[Music]

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:11.850
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In this video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.850 --> 00:00:16.830
we would like to set out an alternative&nbsp;
framework for the fundamental theorem of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.830 --> 00:00:21.990
algebra—or actually the fundamental theorems of&nbsp;
algebra that we talked about last time because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:26.820
there are actually a couple of them that&nbsp;
are closely related. What I want to do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:35.010
reposition these actual theorems to be much more&nbsp;
algebraic, to not actually involve any analysis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.010 --> 00:00:40.380
at least in their statements, so that at least&nbsp;
the statements of the theorems are completely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:48.240
algebraic and sit inside of algebraic reality.&nbsp;
In particular, they should be logically provable.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:53.970
So let's go ahead and lay out precise algebraic&nbsp;
formulations of the fundamental theorems of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.970 --> 00:01:00.810
algebra. This was actually first suggested in my&nbsp;
algebraic topology series quite some years ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.810 --> 00:01:11.130
so it's really an enormous opportunity that we&nbsp;
open up here, and I'm hoping that some viewers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.130 --> 00:01:16.980
will take this up because it's an incredible&nbsp;
opportunity for some young people—or maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:23.100
not-so-young people—to make a really serious&nbsp;
contribution to mathematics. This particular&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:30.030
theorem especially is of fundamental importance&nbsp;
in mathematics; it really is a pillar of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:35.850
as the name suggests. It's crucially&nbsp;
important, and so it's very, very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.850 --> 00:01:44.220
very important that we have a solid formulation&nbsp;
and proof of it. Currently, we don't have that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:49.680
so this is an enormous opportunity for some young&nbsp;
people to become rich and famous on these grounds.

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:57.810
Okay, so this is really among the foremost&nbsp;
challenges in pure mathematics in the current era,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.810 --> 00:02:02.970
and I think it's probably not much of&nbsp;
an exaggeration to say that proving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:10.170
this result—really getting it on a firm&nbsp;
basis—would be as important as any other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:15.900
single mathematical accomplishment in the&nbsp;
20th century. It really is at that level;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:28.080
it's a foundational-level kind of challenge—very,&nbsp;
very important. So, maybe you can do it.

00:02:29.340 --> 00:02:32.550
Alright, so our challenge is to&nbsp;
set up this framework in a purely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:36.360
algebraic way—so really relying on&nbsp;
the basic operations of addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:40.620
multiplication, subtraction, and&nbsp;
division. No transcendental processes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:46.410
no infinite processes being completed,&nbsp;
so none of that implicitly under the rug,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:52.890
surreptitiously. Everything squared away logically&nbsp;
with a finite number of arithmetical steps.

00:02:52.890 --> 00:03:00.900
Okay, so the setup is that of rational complex&nbsp;
numbers. These are not the usual complex numbers;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:07.500
these are actually the true complex numbers. So a&nbsp;
rational complex number is one—it's an expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:17.790
of the form a + bi where a and b are rational&nbsp;
numbers. This is a rather quick way of introducing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:23.730
rational complex numbers. We will also, in a&nbsp;
little while, show you some other ways of thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:31.980
about these things that are perhaps more intuitive&nbsp;
or in the line of data structures, but for now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:37.500
this is familiar enough, I think, to most people:&nbsp;
a + bi, where a and b are rational numbers. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:44.160
the critical point. So these things can be&nbsp;
added in the usual kind of way, and they can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:51.840
be multiplied in this particular way, which really&nbsp;
amounts to the rule that i times i is -1. This bi&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.840 --> 00:04:01.900
and this di become -bd. This creates a field—we&nbsp;
won't say precisely what that means—but a field&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:09.160
with the name rat(C), or rational complex numbers,&nbsp;
which contains the rational numbers in the special&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:15.520
case when the coefficient of i is zero. In that&nbsp;
case, we get something which is a rational number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:20.890
so we can think about the rational complexes&nbsp;
as being an extension of the rational numbers.

00:04:20.890 --> 00:04:25.480
While historically complex numbers were&nbsp;
problematic, when it became apparent that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:29.920
there was a two-dimensional representation&nbsp;
of them, then it was a little bit easier for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:35.470
people to visualize them and understand them.&nbsp;
So this is sometimes called the Argand plane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:41.800
where we take the usual xy-plane and identify&nbsp;
the y-axis with the i-axis. So we have usual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:46.270
rational numbers here and multiples of&nbsp;
i in that direction. That allows us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:53.170
visualize a complex number like 3 + 2i as 3&nbsp;
in this direction and 2i in this direction.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.170 --> 00:05:00.790
So it really corresponds to the point&nbsp;
(3, 2) in sort of an affine sense. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:05.440
we can visualize rational complex numbers&nbsp;
as points in the familiar affine plane.

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:14.410
And now here is the main measurement notion&nbsp;
that we'll need. The quadrance of a rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:26.840
complex number z, which is a + bi, is the rational&nbsp;
number q(z) which is a² + b². So a² + b²—that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:33.560
the quadrance between these two points in&nbsp;
the usual two-dimensional Euclidean plane.

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:42.440
Remarkably, this quantity doesn't really get&nbsp;
officially defined in a complex analysis course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:47.420
which is really quite astounding because&nbsp;
it's an absolutely central and fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:52.940
notion. Unfortunately, most treatments&nbsp;
of complex numbers start by saying,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:57.710
"Let's immediately take the square root of this&nbsp;
and call this the absolute value of the complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:04.070
number." We do not want to do that, okay? We do&nbsp;
not want to use absolute value in this context,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:11.480
which is the square root involved—really an&nbsp;
infinite process. You have the square root of,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:18.320
in this case, for example, 9 + 4, 13—the square&nbsp;
root of 13—that's not something that you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:27.110
access in a standard way with only a finite number&nbsp;
of arithmetical steps. The quadrance, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:34.670
just 13, is of course very easy and pleasant to&nbsp;
work with. So that's a big adjustment that one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.670 --> 00:06:41.030
ought to make when studying complex numbers. So&nbsp;
think about quadrance rather than absolute value.

00:06:41.030 --> 00:06:47.630
And two very important and useful facts about&nbsp;
quadrance: first of all, that the quadrance&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:56.990
of a complex number z is 0 precisely when z =&nbsp;
0. So it goes both ways—if the quadrance is 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.990 --> 00:07:01.970
then the complex number is 0, and it’s&nbsp;
easily seen that if the complex number is 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:08.900
then its quadrance is 0. And this is probably the&nbsp;
most important fact about complex numbers from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:14.120
an elementary point of view: the fact that the&nbsp;
quadrance is multiplicative—that the quadrance of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:21.860
a product z times w with two rational complex&nbsp;
numbers is the product of q(z) times q(w).

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:28.660
Okay, so we're not going to go too far in&nbsp;
this direction for now. The main thing is to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:35.680
understand that we can expand polynomial algebra&nbsp;
or arithmetic from polynomials with only rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:41.800
coefficients to polynomials involving complex&nbsp;
coefficients, and we can replace the idea of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:48.670
plugging in rational values with the idea&nbsp;
of plugging in rational complex values. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:59.830
for example, here in a polynomial P(z) = z⁵ - 2z&nbsp;
+ 3, if, for example, we substitute the complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:07.300
number 1 - ½i, we can sub that in here—that would&nbsp;
involve taking the fifth power of this thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:14.140
subtracting 2 times this, and adding 3. And&nbsp;
one can check that the result of that is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:23.980
complex number -3/16 - 9/32i. So, for example,&nbsp;
if we were looking for a zero of this polynomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.980 --> 00:08:30.370
regarded in this complex setting, then this&nbsp;
would not be a zero because the polynomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:36.550
evaluated at it is not zero. But if we&nbsp;
manage to find a such a complex number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.550 --> 00:08:42.940
such that we do get zeros, then that would&nbsp;
be a zero—a root—of the complex polynomial.

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:48.160
Okay, so now these true fundamental theorems&nbsp;
of algebra statements that we're interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.160 --> 00:08:53.800
in—they really are going to be purely algebraic.&nbsp;
So we want statements that are purely algebraic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.800 --> 00:09:00.910
like they can be understood in principle&nbsp;
by a primary school student. No calculus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.910 --> 00:09:07.390
no analysis, no complicated functions—we&nbsp;
just know how to add, multiply, subtract,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:11.170
and divide, and they have learned a&nbsp;
little bit about these complex numbers.

00:09:11.890 --> 00:09:17.290
Okay, so there are going to be several such&nbsp;
theorems. In the same way as in the previous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:22.870
video, we had two different theorems—here,&nbsp;
there will be two different theorems as well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:30.090
and they have some increasing sophistication. And&nbsp;
I want to reiterate this very important point:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:38.100
we have no proper proof of these statements.&nbsp;
None of the many, many proofs that have been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:44.250
given are logically correct because they&nbsp;
all implicitly, one way or the other,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:52.260
assume somewhere or another infinite&nbsp;
processes. But one way or the other,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:56.970
if you look at all the proofs, they're all&nbsp;
doing this, and we want to avoid that. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:56.970 --> 00:10:02.940
want to understand the situation so deeply that&nbsp;
we can see the essential algebraic aspects of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:10.290
them. So this is an incredible opportunity&nbsp;
for smart, careful, and precise thinkers.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:16.770
Now, 50 years from now, people will&nbsp;
be jealous of you for having this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.770 --> 00:10:24.270
opportunity to be able to prove such an&nbsp;
important, crucially important theorem—an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:30.390
absolute foundational aspect for people—all of&nbsp;
algebra. That’s waiting for us in the future,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:35.880
that’s to come. Maybe some of you&nbsp;
can be involved. Very exciting!

00:10:36.900 --> 00:10:40.110
Alright, so here's the first true&nbsp;
fundamental theorem of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:45.480
and it's necessarily a little bit more&nbsp;
complicated to state than the usual one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:52.350
because it's more precise and pins things down&nbsp;
more carefully. And so we pay a little bit of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:57.480
a price for being more accurate and staying&nbsp;
in the algebraic world. So, what is it? For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.480 --> 00:11:11.280
any non-constant polynomial P(z) = a₀ + a₁z +&nbsp;
... + aₙzⁿ, we'll assume that this aₙ is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:19.110
equal to 0 with n greater than or equal to 1. So&nbsp;
this non-constant means that the degree of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.110 --> 00:11:29.310
polynomial is at least 1, and these coefficients&nbsp;
a₀, a₁ up to aₙ are all rational complex numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:38.660
Given such a polynomial, and given a natural&nbsp;
number K which is bigger than or equal to 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.660 --> 00:11:47.600
the statement is that there is a w&nbsp;
= a + bi, a rational complex number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:56.720
with the property that the quadrance&nbsp;
of P(w) is less than or equal to 1/K.

00:11:56.720 --> 00:12:08.330
So you're given a polynomial, and then someone&nbsp;
says, "Let's choose K = 10" or whatever—there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:16.670
some particular K chosen—and then your job is&nbsp;
to find an approximate zero, not really a zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:22.220
but an approximate zero. What does that mean? It&nbsp;
means a complex number—a rational complex number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:27.500
crucially—so that when you plug it into the&nbsp;
polynomial, you get this other complex number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:37.400
P(w), and when you take the quadrance of that,&nbsp;
it's small. The quadrance being small means that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:45.890
the complex number is close to zero. Well, close&nbsp;
in the sense that its quadrance is at most 1/K.

00:12:45.890 --> 00:12:51.350
Okay, so let's have a look at an example&nbsp;
because we like explicit, concrete examples.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:51.350 --> 00:13:03.050
Here is a polynomial P(z) = z⁶ + 3z² + z + 1.&nbsp;
In the ordinary, say, rational number domain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:08.660
this is what the graph looks like. It has some&nbsp;
kind of shape like this, and it's quite clear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:15.890
that it's not going to cross the x-axis, so it&nbsp;
doesn't have a traditional zero. At times gone by,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.890 --> 00:13:22.370
people would have said, "This function doesn't&nbsp;
have a zero." But over the complex plane, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.370 --> 00:13:29.600
a wider story, and we can get some approximate&nbsp;
zeros at least. So let's see how that works.

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:34.850
So the ingredients for the fundamental&nbsp;
theorem of algebra part one as we've set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:34.850 --> 00:13:41.180
out are a polynomial like this together&nbsp;
with some resolution level K, say K = 30.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:48.650
So if we're given these two quantities, then&nbsp;
we want to find a complex number w = a + bi,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.650 --> 00:13:59.120
crucially a rational complex number, such that&nbsp;
the quadrance of P(w) is less than or equal to,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:06.800
say, 1/30. So we want that when we plug this&nbsp;
thing into here, we're getting a complex number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:12.590
which is in quite a close proximity&nbsp;
to zero—within the quadrance of 1/30.

00:14:12.590 --> 00:14:22.520
Okay, so I have found such a zero for you,&nbsp;
and here it is: it's -1/6 + 1/2i. If we take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.360
this complex number and plug it in here,&nbsp;
we calculate the sixth power and so on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:34.040
and make this calculation, then we get&nbsp;
this complex number 127/729 - 13/648i.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:45.950
And if we call that thing v, then this&nbsp;
complex number v has quadrance—well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:50.390
it's that thing squared plus that thing squared,&nbsp;
and that turns out to be this: 1045945/34012224.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.910 --> 00:23:10.560
Let me kind of line them up here so you can kind&nbsp;
of see it's basically like 1/34, and that's just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:22.440
a little bit less than 1/25. So if our K value&nbsp;
was 25, then this would be a linear factorization&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:29.190
of the polynomial which is approximate, but&nbsp;
which is within the resolution of K = 25.

00:23:32.440 --> 00:23:38.200
I think it's quite interesting. I think the&nbsp;
numbers are interesting. I think it's pleasant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:46.510
and also curious that the zeros that we're&nbsp;
getting here are relatively simple fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.510 --> 00:23:51.220
right? They're not very big. This is&nbsp;
a reasonably decent-sized polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:57.040
and it’s curious that we can get to this&nbsp;
pretty good approximation because actually,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:02.860
the sum of all these five or six quadrances&nbsp;
is for a total of less than 1/25. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:06.670
doing pretty well with relatively&nbsp;
simple-minded factors, you might say.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:15.340
Which brings us to the interesting question: okay,&nbsp;
so just how—how can we generalize this kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:15.340 --> 00:24:21.040
thing? You know, given this polynomial, and we&nbsp;
understand its coefficients, given a K value,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:27.820
how complicated do these zeros have to be?&nbsp;
In other words, how big are the numerators&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:34.930
and denominators typically going to be so that&nbsp;
we get within the resolution required? This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:34.930 --> 00:24:41.140
an example of a different kind of question&nbsp;
that arises when we give up on our abstract,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:49.090
theoretical, pie-in-the-sky kind of explanation&nbsp;
of what's going on and return to a more concrete,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:49.090 --> 00:24:54.670
computational, "let's see what actually&nbsp;
happens" point of view. So we give up on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:54.670 --> 00:25:01.930
the dreaming, we face the reality, but more&nbsp;
interesting questions arrive. We see more;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:05.920
we get in more contact with real mathematics.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:13.810
So I'm hopeful that's what we'll do—finding&nbsp;
proofs for these theorems, that those proofs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:13.810 --> 00:25:21.820
will have a strong computational bias. I think it&nbsp;
will involve having more insight than we currently&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.820 --> 00:25:27.010
have. So if you're aspiring to prove these&nbsp;
things, the first thing you should do is have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.010 --> 00:25:31.330
a good look at the classical proofs. There are&nbsp;
a lot of great ideas in those classical proofs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:31.330 --> 00:25:38.170
okay? You will want to understand the basic ideas&nbsp;
there—there are all these topological ideas—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.170 --> 00:25:43.900
then you want to wrestle with how you’re going&nbsp;
to restate those topological arguments without&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:50.200
making all these real-number assumptions about&nbsp;
continuity, and how you can get it down to just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:50.200 --> 00:25:58.690
algebra. So it’s a very major challenge. I&nbsp;
think it really is probably useful to keep in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:04.420
mind this computational question. It's not just a&nbsp;
question of proving these things, but really what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.420 --> 00:26:10.120
we'd like to do is to have some understanding&nbsp;
of how we find those zeros. Given a polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:19.750
given a K, how do we actually find an approximate&nbsp;
zero of that degree of accuracy? What do we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:19.750 --> 00:26:24.580
to do? Can we actually give a computational&nbsp;
proof of these theorems? That really matters.

00:26:24.580 --> 00:26:30.280
And I also want to mention that there’s another&nbsp;
challenge lurking in the background. After you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:34.540
start thinking about this for a little while,&nbsp;
you'll realize that the first two theorems that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:40.390
I've given you are not the end of the story.&nbsp;
There are naturally some further extensions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:47.470
that you want to enunciate and then pin&nbsp;
down. So I'm not going to say what those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:51.580
are at this point—I might do later on,&nbsp;
maybe in my algebraic calculus course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:56.440
which I'm thinking about and sort&nbsp;
of slowly working on. But anyway,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:56.440 --> 00:27:00.940
there are some fundamental theorems of algebra&nbsp;
part three and part four that are sort of out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:00.940 --> 00:27:07.420
there that are worth investigating, and I'll&nbsp;
leave it to you to figure out what those might be.

00:27:07.420 --> 00:27:13.240
So I know that there will be a fair number of&nbsp;
mathematicians who are not going to be happy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:13.240 --> 00:27:21.070
with this new direction. It’s destabilizing;&nbsp;
it's disconcerting to realize that something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:21.070 --> 00:27:27.070
that you had accepted for a long time was&nbsp;
in fact not really entirely correct—that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:27.070 --> 00:27:31.720
there's this major logical gap there.&nbsp;
But nevertheless, it's an opportunity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:38.380
for a lot of invigorated discussion and&nbsp;
development in the subject, I think.

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:43.770
In our next video, I want to talk a little&nbsp;
bit more about the fundamental theorem and&nbsp;&nbsp;

